<article id="post-663" class="post-663 page type-page status-publish hentry">
	<header class="entry-header">
		<h1 class="entry-title">Special Series on Custodial Research</h1>
	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	<div class="entry-content">
		<p style="text-align: justify;">In this series, hosted by <a href="http://http://www.crim.ox.ac.uk">the Centre for Criminology</a>, researchers will join with criminal justice practitioners to discuss the challenges of conducting research in prisons and immigration detention centres. The six, two-hour, lunch-time seminars will run over the course of the academic year, 2 per term. Each seminar will focus on a specific aspect of conducting custodial research, ranging from gaining access to common ethical dilemmas and disseminating results, with an emphasis on knowledge exchange. We have opted for this format in order to facilitate the participation of the practitioners.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Each seminar will be recorded and podcast on the Centre for Criminology website via the University of Oxford iTunes account. The series will be supported by a page on the <a href="http://bordercriminologies.law.ox.ac.uk"><em>Border Criminologies</em> </a>website on which additional material, including Powerpoint slides and any lecture notes and discussion papers, will also be posted and made free to download. As such it will have a life beyond the seminar series, remaining as a virtual resource after the series is over.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Each session will be lead by a specialist and will be open to anyone in the university as well as to students elsewhere. The programme will be of particular interest to graduate students in the social sciences working on imprisonment, immigration control, and criminal justice policy. In Oxford students are working on these topics across a number of departments including geography, anthropology, sociology, criminology, political science, and psychology. The programme will provide a valuable ‘central’ resource for these students and a bridge across disciplinary boundaries. Seminars will include plenty of time and opportunity for doctoral students to discuss the problems they foresee or encounter in planning and implementing their fieldwork.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The seminar series will showcase the expertise in the Centre for Criminology on research across a range of custodial sites. Designed and lead by Dr Mary Bosworth, Reader in Criminology, it will involve five additional members of staff: Drs Ben Bradford, Ines Hasselberg, Alpa Parmar, Sharon Shalev and Sarah Turnbull who will present alongside external practitioners. Each staff member will draw directly on his or her applied research experiences to explore ethical and practical challenges in research design, data collection and dissemination, as well as methods for resolving them.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">By involving practitioners, from the government, an NGO, and private security firms, (Ministry of Justice, HM Prison Service, the Prison Reform Trust, Sodexho and Mitie), this series builds on the Center for Criminology’s strong tradition of ‘knowledge exchange,’ a key aim as well of the Doctoral Training Centre (DTC). This arrangement will offer students a unique opportunity to network with custodial representatives, well known to the event organizer and interested in facilitating research projects. It will also remind participants of the varied audiences of their work. When conducting research in custodial environments, we need to take prisoners and prison officers, as well as policy makers, into account. As part of the series, the Centre for Criminology will establish a ‘knowledge exchange fellowship,’ to enable other practitioners to attend the series from outside the university, spending up to two weeks at the Centre for Criminology. They will be invited to contribute their perspective and experience of research to the website and to meet with students attending the seminar series.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Those who take part in this specialist seminar series will, in short, have an invaluable opportunity to discuss with academic experts and practitioners the key issues facing anyone conducting research in a custodial environment: access, ethics, and impact.   The series will benefit those about to embark on doctoral projects as well as experienced researchers. Participants will receive a short reading list devised by the series organizer to complement the discussion.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The series will be widely advertised through social media such as the Centre for Criminology (@OxfordCrim) and<em> <a href="http://bordercriminologies.law.ox.ac.uk">Border Criminologies</a></em> (@bordercrim) Twitter feeds as well as their blogs and the Border Criminologies Facebook account. It will also be advertised via the Research Methods Hub term card across the division at <a href="https://owa.nexus.ox.ac.uk/owa/redir.aspx?C=brnJUHxK6kOmksDX5qU0WBtVgmX_v9AIjWKHPfPdfDIE-HlKrgBnCvq_LuUs0lUSc1VPQfG7t-M.&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.dtcsocsci.ox.ac.uk">www.dtcsocsci.ox.ac.uk</a> and in the <a href="http://www.ox.ac.uk/gazette/">University Gazette</a>, etc. In order to attract students and scholars beyond the university, the series could be advertised on <a href="https://owa.nexus.ox.ac.uk/owa/redir.aspx?C=brnJUHxK6kOmksDX5qU0WBtVgmX_v9AIjWKHPfPdfDIE-HlKrgBnCvq_LuUs0lUSc1VPQfG7t-M.&amp;URL=http%3a%2f%2fwww.ncrm.ac.uk%2ftraining%2f">http://www.ncrm.ac.uk/training/</a> as advanced training. Students who attend can claim bursaries from the <a href="http://researchtraining.socsci.ox.ac.uk/home-dtc">ESRC DTC</a>.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->
